##Half business, no goods to sell, mobile phones offline channel difficult to start the year

Two weeks after the Lunar New Year holiday, it was supposed to be the peak season for mobile phone sales. Tens of thousands of mobile phone distributors and retailers across the country are gearing up to start work, but the outbreak has poured cold water on the market.

In the face of the spread of the epidemic, large and small mobile phone brand stores in the post-festival announced the delay in opening.

On Feb. 1, apple officially announced that it would temporarily close all its stores in mainland China until Feb. 9. This was followed by the closure of Samsung's China flagship store in Shanghai until February 9.

Domestic brands have also had to close stores to stave off the epidemic. Brands such as OPPO, Vivo and Xiaomi have all announced delays in some areas, while the timing for the resumption of many stores in the hard-hit areas remains uncertain. In addition to the brands, as of February 14, although a small number of stores have opened, but the vast majority of the state is closed.

This has undoubtedly caused quite a shock to the handset manufacturers. Offline has been an important battleground for the ovs, as has Huawei, which rose to prominence offline last year. Early Internet start ups also accelerated their offline presence in 2019: Xiaomi opened more than 100 stores late last year, and now has more than 6,000 stores; and glory has more than 2,000 offline stores and franchises, offline sales have leveled off.

Even if the pneumonia is brought under control in late February or March, China's smartphone shipments will fall 30 percent in the first quarter and 5 percent below expectations for the full year of 2020, according to the latest report from Strategy Analytics. Guo Mingxu, an analyst at Tianfeng securities, is even gloomier, predicting that shipments in the domestic mobile phone market will fall by nearly 60% in the spring from a year earlier, and by 15% in the full year.

The entire mobile phone industry chain has been enveloped by the haze of the epidemic, once played a large area under the line is like walking on thin ice.

###The manufacturer is losing money and the channel is out of stock

The distributors were the first to smell the danger.

After five years in the mobile channel business in Huaqiang north, he has set up shop in the Longsheng Various Nationalities Autonomous County communications market. As usual, the holiday season is the busiest time of the year, but the outbreak has prompted stores in Huaqiang north to open after February 18 and Longsheng Various Nationalities Autonomous County to postpone the holiday until March 6.

No opening means no money. Although Chen Jinwang's goods are mainly sold through online channels, he is still not optimistic about this year's sales. "basically cut my business in half, " he said.

Compared to business cold, now more let Huaqiang north numerous channels are worried about the lack of supply. On the one hand, the mall closed, the store in order to store after the peak season inventory can not be proposed. On the other hand, the Hong Kong government announced the closure of the four major ports leading to Shenzhen, which is an important channel for many distributors in Huaqiang north to purchase goods. As a result of the "closure" , no goods could be imported, and "one out and one out" .

As the upstream supply chain delayed the resumption of time, the domestic mobile phone market in the first quarter of supply will also face shortage pressure. Accordingly, the channel in the hands of the machine price also ushered in the overall small increase. Chen Jinwang is currently stepping up efforts to find goods from the hands of peers, hoping to temporarily make up for the shortage of goods. And Chen Jinwang channels like there are many, he added more than a dozen Huaqiang north wechat group from time to time pop-up for goods news.

"Now very few people specialize in offline, mostly online, a small part offline, " a channel in the group told interface news, although the overall consumption of the Spring Festival has decreased, but the money online was enough to get him through the outbreak. What he is most looking forward to now is Huaqiang north open market, so that he can be in the store several hundred units inventory clear.

Daninel Lves, an analyst with wedbush securities, said that the epidemic in China has caused traffic restrictions in major cities, and the number of passengers in cities such as Shanghai, Guangzhou and Shenzhen has dropped significantly, plans to sell 1m iphones in the major cities were delayed from the first quarter to the second quarter. Guo Mingwei analysis, the current market has nearly 60 million unsalable mobile phones.

Zhang Hang, head of marketing for an area in east China of Vivo, told interface news that in his area of responsibility, the annual Spring Festival was a bottom line of 500,000 net profit, while sales this Spring Festival were down 75 percent from last year, adding to the burden of rent and personnel costs, led directly to a loss of 200,000 yuan.

Zhang hang responsible for the jurisdiction of nearly half of the non-locals, generally during the New Year there are two consumption points: home before the festival and after the rework. Zhang hang revealed that the pre-festival sales were basically unaffected, but the post-festival outbreak point is far away. "based on the current situation, even if we return to work, there will not be large aggregate consumption. This node is basically useless. "

###Store traffic drops, fears of store closures

Losing a node can basically drag down a store's sales for an entire year.

"The impact is limited for our manufacturers, after all, our operating costs are not particularly high, but it is a heavy blow for the stores, " Zhang said, adding: "For a mom-and-pop store with slightly better business, compared to previous years, the mobile phone sales business this Spring Festival made nearly 40,000 less, in addition to the operating business and the loss of rent, it can be seen as a loss of sixty thousand, which is close to one-fifth of their annual income. "

Zhang estimates that the damage is still within the reach of many shopkeepers, but for some smaller retailers, another month could be life and death for them -- as if they would have to pay tens of thousands of dollars in store rentals, and take a hidden loss. As inventories pile up, existing older machines will be harder to sell once new ones are released in the first quarter.

Gu Hua, the owner of a Huawei authorized experience store in Guangxi, shares the same anxiety.

Gu Hua's store opened in a well-known shopping mall in Guangxi, the store in the past the flow of customers mainly rely on the surrounding residents and mall customers. Since the local prevention and control measures have become more stringent, the flow of shopping malls immediately cut 90% . The store used to sell 15-20 units a day, but this time slipped to only a few, and even one day the turnover of 0. She estimates that she has made at least 30,000 less this Spring Festival.

Huawei has always had certain standards for its stores, and monthly sales as a percentage of Tiku's total are part of those standards, which Gu had worried would be difficult to meet in the midst of the epidemic. Fortunately, in view of the impact of the epidemic, Huawei has made certain changes to the assessment criteria for specialty stores: In the past, stores were required to achieve a certain amount of sales under the prescribed number of deliveries, but now stores can, according to the sales situation, self-determination pick up the number of goods, to a certain extent ease the pressure on the store.

In fact, as more and more people develop the habit of online consumption, the business of the offline shop is getting harder and harder to do. A few years ago, operators'subsidies and manufacturers'subsidies were important sources of revenue for stores. But because the revenue profit of the operator drops ceaselessly, can compress marketing cost further, add the mobile phone market also is accelerating shuffle, in order to protect oneself, the manufacturer is in likewise reducing to channel subsidy.

In such a situation, the store can only rely on selling mobile phones to make a difference, but the market as a whole is not depressed. In the fourth quarter of 2019, shipments of 85.3 million smartphones in China were down 15 percent from the same period a year earlier, according to Canalys, leading to 11 consecutive quarters of decline.

Many retailers are pinning their hopes on 2020 in anticipation of a wave of changes to 5G, but Zhang fears a wave of closures if it is delayed.

###WECHAT sells goods

In response to the epidemic in the store under the impact of the difficulties, the major mobile phone brands have introduced subsidies to help the offline store to tide over the difficulties. In some areas, Vivo is also known to be offering salary subsidies and bonus payments based on past sales and length of service. According to interface news, individuals can receive a cumulative subsidy of hundreds of dollars.

"It's a bit more difficult, but we're also looking for a way out, " Gu said. In addition to waiting for the epidemic to pass, brick-and-mortar stores are also tapping into Huawei's resources at the mall side, hoping to implement some online-to-offline sales programs. For example, in the mall side, with Vientiane on-line members for Bundling Drainage; in the Huawei side, is considering the use of company resources for live delivery, near the store delivery, to speed up turnover inventory.

Gu Hua expresses, under the impact of E-commerce, even if did not have this epidemic, this kind of on-line and off-line combination of marketing exploration will also be the inevitable trend of entity store development. In her view, if we can actively access these resources, the store is enough to survive the epidemic. But in the more remote counties and towns, many small and medium-sized retail stores can get little resource support, only self-help.

Yang Qian, a mobile phone salesman, worries about business in Xinhua County, Loudi, Hunan Province. She has not been able to return to the county because of the road closure in her hometown.

But under, she can rely on the customer network that accumulates at ordinary times, sell a mobile phone on Wechat. From the Spring Festival until now, she has been on-line collation of product information, do wechat guide shopping. Yang Qian told interface news, because the county circle is small, with word-of-mouth recommendations between customers, some people are willing to order directly from wechat. Though business isn't as good as it was last Spring Festival, one or two sales a day, along with the recent surge in tablet buyers, have helped fill some of the gap.

"The biggest lesson I learned from this outbreak is that I can no longer sit in the store and wait for customers to come to my door, " said Yang Qian, who along with her peers is starting to build their own customer database and preparing to maintain relationships on wechat on an irregular basis. At the same time, the store to further increase the publicity on the short video platform, the store manager himself planning, shooting content, but also accumulated a few hundred small fans.

IDC released a report on the impact of the epidemic on the mobile phone industry in the New Year, saying that due to the short-term on-line purchase of mobile phone users there are part of the original habit of off-line purchase, but "forced" to switch to the online crowd, if this part of the population can buy a machine online to obtain a relatively good experience, the future will be expected to spread and continue online consumer habits. As a result, offline brick-and-mortar stores can only improve their competitiveness by enhancing their services and operations.

For offline stores, Spring Festival, May Day, November 11, Winter and summer holidays are small peaks, lost a season of retailers can only place all hope in the next outbreak point. "We are looking at the news of the epidemic every day and waiting for it to get better. If we can make it to May Day, then this year's business can still be saved, " Yang said.
